pener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;@&lt;span&gt;elduvelle&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; I recommend to read the thread by &lt;span class="h-card"&gt;&lt;a class="u-url mention" href="https://mas.to/@kissane" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;@&lt;span&gt;kissane&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; or its blog post, since she made a great job in summarizing the feelings of twitter migrants:&lt;a href="https://mas.to/@kissane/110793942888550843" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;https://&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="ellipsis"&gt;mas.to/@kissane/11079394288855&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;0843&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</description><guid isPermaLink="false">111001360357251023</guid><pubDate>Sun, 03 Sep 2023 13:05:42 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Earl K. Miller</title><link>https://fediscience.org/@ekmiller/111001540224291204</link><description>Jamming with Brad Postle at the Cognitive Neuroscience Society meeting, San Francisco, March 2023.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;a href="https://files.mastodon.social/cache/media_attachments/files/111/001/540/306/306/182/original/a86761614af63c0d.jpg"&gt;&lt;img src="https://files.mastodon.social/cache/media_attachments/files/111/001/540/306/306/182/original/a86761614af63c0d.jpg" alt="Mastodon image" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</description><guid isPermaLink="false">111001540365806626</guid><pubDate>Sun, 03 Sep 2023 13:51:27 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Eugen Rochko</title><link>https://mastodon.social/@Gargron/111001593286010779</link><description>The fragmentation among friends that follows Twitter’s collapse is exactly the kind of problem that Mastodon and the social web solves for. Imagine that you don’t have to pick and choose which new platform to adopt, or make and maintain a million accounts—because you can follow anyone regardless of which platform they’re on. That’s our reality.</description><guid isPermaLink="false">111001619990520684</guid><pubDate>Sun, 03 Sep 2023 14:11:44 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Manlio De Domenico</title><link>https://mathstodon.xyz/@manlius/111001683644081371</link><description>Following up an interesting exchange, I'd like to ask you:- how would you define a "machine" broadly speaking?- is your definition covering a broad spectrum, such as molecular machines, man made machines, computers, etc?- are you sure that your definition does not lead to defining as "machine" a forest fire or an hurricane? - which argument would you use to characterize the differences between a molecular machine like kinesin and a mechanical machine like an old watch? Does it work too for a whole cell or the human brain? (at a high level of abstraction, of course) I have some ideas to share based on universal Turing machines and complexity science, but would like to get more inputs, first.As usual, I try to bootstrap the discussion by involving a diverse pool of friends and good thinkers: &lt;span class="h-card"&gt;&lt;a class="u-url mention" href="https://neuromatch.social/@PessoaBrain" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;@&lt;span&gt;PessoaBrain&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="h-card"&gt;&lt;a class="u-url mention" href="https://social.skewed.de/@tiago" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;@&lt;span&gt;tiago&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="h-card"&gt;&lt;a class="u-url mention" href="https://qoto.org/@lmrocha" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;@&lt;span&gt;lmrocha&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="h-card"&gt;&lt;a class="u-url mention" href="https://fediscience.org/@thilo" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;@&lt;span&gt;thilo&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="h-card"&gt;&lt;a class="u-url mention" href="https://neuromatch.social/@kordinglab" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;@&lt;span&gt;kordinglab&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="h-card"&gt;&lt;a class="u-url mention" href="https://neuromatch.social/@NicoleCRust" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;@&lt;span&gt;NicoleCRust&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="h-card"&gt;&lt;a class="u-url mention" href="https://mstdn.science/@hirokisayama" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;@&lt;span&gt;hirokisayama&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="h-card"&gt;&lt;a class="u-url mention" href="https://mstdn.social/@WiringtheBrain" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;@&lt;span&gt;WiringtheBrain&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;a href="https://files.mastodon.social/cache/media_attachments/files/111/001/683/728/907/898/original/f42f212baddd4bc3.jpg"&gt;&lt;img src="https://files.mastodon.social/cache/media_attachments/files/111/001/683/728/907/898/original/f42f212baddd4bc3.jpg" alt="Mastodon image" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</description><guid isPermaLink="false">111001683912096663</guid><pubDate>Sun, 03 Sep 2023 14:27:56 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Luiz Pessoa</title><link>https://neuromatch.social/@PessoaBrain/111002005766625769</link><description>&lt;span class="h-card" translate="no"&gt;&lt;a class="u-url mention" href="https://mathstodon.xyz/@manlius" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;@&lt;span&gt;manlius&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="h-card" translate="no"&gt;&lt;a class="u-url mention" href="https://social.perceptiveconstructs.com/users/carlos" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;@&lt;span&gt;carlos&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="h-card" translate="no"&gt;&lt;a class="u-url mention" href="https://fediscience.org/@thilo" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;@&lt;span&gt;thilo&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="h-card" translate="no"&gt;&lt;a class="u-url mention" href="https://mstdn.science/@hirokisayama" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;@&lt;span&gt;hirokisayama&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="h-card" translate="no"&gt;&lt;a class="u-url mention" href="https://mstdn.social/@WiringtheBrain" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;@&lt;span&gt;WiringtheBrain&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="h-card" translate="no"&gt;&lt;a class="u-url mention" href="https://neuromatch.social/@kordinglab" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;@&lt;span&gt;kordinglab&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="h-card" translate="no"&gt;&lt;a class="u-url mention" href="https://neuromatch.social/@NicoleCRust" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;@&lt;span&gt;NicoleCRust&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="h-card" translate="no"&gt;&lt;a class="u-url mention" href="https://qoto.org/@lmrocha" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;@&lt;span&gt;lmrocha&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="h-card" translate="no"&gt;&lt;a class="u-url mention" href="https://social.skewed.de/@tiago" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;@&lt;span&gt;tiago&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; I'll think more carefully. But it's it useful to think about digital vs analog computing? After all the theory of binary computing is very well developed but that of "computing over the reals" has really struggled.There was some excitement excitement in the early 1990s when Stephen Smale was pushing out with several others.  There are also some recent connections with attempts to understand Navier-Stokes a bit better. Did you see the link to "water computes" work in a recent post of mine on bsky? It was serious work, but don't know how useful to you.</description><guid isPermaLink="false">111002006043944111</guid><pubDate>Sun, 03 Sep 2023 15:49:51 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Earl K. Miller</title><link>https://fediscience.org/@ekmiller/111002131854218279</link><descr